<p>In order to use Herocutter with the <a href="http://www.github.com/heroku/heroku">heroku gem</a>, you need to first install the <a href="http://www.github.com/hone/heroku_herocutter">Herocutter plugin</a>:</p>

<p><code>heroku plugins:install git://github.com/hone/heroku_herocutter.git</code></p>

<p>The following commands will then be available:</p>

<p><pre><code>plugins:install &lt;plugin name&gt; # install the plugin from herocutter
plugins:push [&lt;git_uri&gt;]      # push plugin up to herocutter
plugins:list -r               # will list plugins on herocutter
</code></pre></p>

<h4><a name="install">Install</a></h4>
<p>To install a plugin, just pass a plugin name to <code>heroku plugins:install</code>:</p>

<p><pre><code>heroku plugins:install colorize_console</code></pre></p>

<h4><a name="push">Push</a></h4>
<p>To push a plugin up remotely, you need to sign up and verify your herocutter account.  On the <a href="/profile">profile page</a> you'll find your API Key, you'll need to put this in your ~/.heroku/herocutter file in the format described on that page.  Now you can cd into the git repo of your heroku plugin, and do a <code>plugins:push</code>:

<p><pre><code>heroku plugins:push</code></pre></p>

<p>By default, herocutter will pull the git uri from origin and use that.  If a GitHub uri is detected, it will automatically push up the read only uri.  The name will be based off the uri.  The prefix 'heroku_' is removed if it is there.  You can also override the uri by passing it into the push command:</p>

<p><pre><code>heroku plugins:push git://somesite.com/some_plugin.git</code></pre></p>

<h4><a name="list">List</a></h4>
<p>To see a list of available plugins from herocutter run <code>heroku plugins:list -r</code>.</p>

<p><pre><code>$ heroku plugins:list -r

*** REMOTE PLUGINS ***

colorize_console
herocutter
switch_command
tab_complete_console
</code></pre></p>

<p><code>heroku plugins:list</code> without the <code>-r</code> will return the list of locally installed ones.</p>
